Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.510
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress, in Washington DC.

00:00:04.510 --> 00:00:22.920
[ Silence ]

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:24.720
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Hi there,
my name is Nicholas Brown

00:00:24.720 --> 00:00:27.080
and I'm a music specialist
with the Library of Congress.

00:00:27.080 --> 00:00:30.380
It's my great pleasure to
introduce you to Thomas Wilkins

00:00:30.380 --> 00:00:32.930
who is the music director
of the Omaha Symphony

00:00:32.930 --> 00:00:35.740
and principal conductor of
the Hollywood Bowl Orchestra.

00:00:35.740 --> 00:00:37.140
Thank you [inaudible]
for being here.

00:00:37.140 --> 00:00:38.440
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: No problem.

00:00:38.440 --> 00:00:41.270
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: We are here today
commemorating the Shift Festival

00:00:41.270 --> 00:00:42.570
of American Orchestras.

00:00:42.570 --> 00:00:43.870
Could you tell us a bit about that

00:00:43.870 --> 00:00:45.170
and your involvement
in the festival?

00:00:45.170 --> 00:00:47.920
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: I was just
asked to serve on a panel

00:00:47.920 --> 00:00:51.460
to discuss really one of
the things that Shift is all

00:00:51.460 --> 00:00:56.100
about is redefining or shifting
if you will, the orchestra's role

00:00:56.100 --> 00:00:58.580
in the communities that they serve.

00:00:58.580 --> 00:01:03.180
And with the hopes that in each
case specific to the community

00:01:03.180 --> 00:01:06.630 position:56%
that they're in that it would
extend beyond just playing concerts.

00:01:06.630 --> 00:01:11.010
And the orchestras that I have
been involved in, involved with,

00:01:11.010 --> 00:01:14.910
and even now, we have
always been about that.

00:01:14.910 --> 00:01:17.700
And so they thought perhaps I
was a good person to come in

00:01:17.700 --> 00:01:19.000
and make up some answers.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:20.300
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Great.

00:01:20.300 --> 00:01:22.610
So the festival is being
co-presented by the Kennedy Center

00:01:22.610 --> 00:01:24.480
and also the Washington Arts

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:27.380
and the Library was a partner
today for the symposium.

00:01:27.380 --> 00:01:30.720
What is your impression of these,
that your principal presenters

00:01:30.720 --> 00:01:33.520
at the festival and the
impact that they're having

00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:36.480
with changing the narrative
about orchestras in this country?

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:40.920
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: I think the fact
that they actually are big voices

00:01:40.920 --> 00:01:44.680 position:56%
in the industry is really important.

00:01:44.680 --> 00:01:47.500
You know, they're, in
some parts of a country

00:01:47.500 --> 00:01:50.840
where orchestras are
small, and they have quote

00:01:50.840 --> 00:01:52.660
on quote the services, the burn.

00:01:52.660 --> 00:01:56.830
By that what I mean is they
have plenty of musician time

00:01:56.830 --> 00:01:59.610
that they can do things
more creatively sometimes

00:01:59.610 --> 00:02:02.170
in a larger organization,
larger organizations

00:02:02.170 --> 00:02:06.370 position:56%
with major orchestras really haven't
had to do those things before.

00:02:06.370 --> 00:02:12.400
So now that we are all
figuring out that no one needs

00:02:12.400 --> 00:02:16.420
to be left behind regardless of
what size setting that you're from,

00:02:16.420 --> 00:02:18.610
I think it's really important

00:02:18.610 --> 00:02:22.130
that the major players are also the
ones waiving the banners as well.

00:02:22.130 --> 00:02:23.510
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Can you
tell us a little bit

00:02:23.510 --> 00:02:26.770 position:56%
about what you're doing specifically
in Omaha and with Hollywood Bowl

00:02:26.770 --> 00:02:28.890
in terms of engaging new audiences

00:02:28.890 --> 00:02:33.820
and perhaps changing the public's
perception about orchestra music?

00:02:33.820 --> 00:02:41.120
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: For me it
starts with, from the basic premise

00:02:41.120 --> 00:02:45.000
that music is life
altering and life affirming.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:50.090
You know as I said to the
group earlier I was a kid born

00:02:50.090 --> 00:02:53.780
to a single mother on welfare in a
housing project, no predisposition

00:02:53.780 --> 00:02:55.680
to classical music whatsoever.

00:02:55.680 --> 00:02:58.280
So that when I heard the
orchestra for the first time

00:02:58.280 --> 00:03:01.660
at eight years old, that
was what I wanted to do.

00:03:01.660 --> 00:03:08.820
I didn't have words to describe
how impacted I was but it meant

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:12.770
that all the critical life choice
questions that kids are faced

00:03:12.770 --> 00:03:14.780
with today were answered
for me by default

00:03:14.780 --> 00:03:16.690
because I had fallen
in love with music.

00:03:16.690 --> 00:03:18.150
Do I go to college?

00:03:18.150 --> 00:03:20.300
What's the nature of my friends?

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:22.910
Where do I find myself when
there's no adult supervision?

00:03:22.910 --> 00:03:26.670
All of those questions were
answered because of music.

00:03:26.670 --> 00:03:32.750
So if I believe and incidentally
that that says more about the power

00:03:32.750 --> 00:03:35.090
of music than it does about me.

00:03:35.090 --> 00:03:38.970
So if I believe that, then
that gift of the power

00:03:38.970 --> 00:03:42.050
of music should be
handed to as many people

00:03:42.050 --> 00:03:46.090
in as many possible ways
as we can come up with.

00:03:46.090 --> 00:03:50.790
And so we've always done, we've
always had, especially in a place

00:03:50.790 --> 00:03:53.950
like Omaha, community
partners that range anywhere

00:03:53.950 --> 00:03:56.700
from the Omaha Housing Authority
to Girls Inc to University

00:03:56.700 --> 00:04:02.290
of Nebraska Medical Center to
hospice care and we don't walk

00:04:02.290 --> 00:04:03.910 position:56%
with a program that says, here we're

00:04:03.910 --> 00:04:06.130
from the government,
we're here to help.

00:04:06.130 --> 00:04:08.260 position:56%
We want to know what your needs are.

00:04:08.260 --> 00:04:12.500
And in some of those cases
it's just about access

00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:14.600
to a place that's different
from the place

00:04:14.600 --> 00:04:15.900
that they spend more of their time.

00:04:15.900 --> 00:04:18.350
And that place for us happens
to be the concert hall.

00:04:18.350 --> 00:04:22.490
And low and behold, in that
place they get the gift of music,

00:04:22.490 --> 00:04:25.930
a world that they didn't think had
any relation to them whatsoever.

00:04:25.930 --> 00:04:30.530
So those are the kinds of things
that we do in Omaha and of course

00:04:30.530 --> 00:04:36.330
at the Hollywood Bowl we are very
much committed to our YOLA program,

00:04:36.330 --> 00:04:41.690
Youth Orchestra of Los Angeles, and
now we've been doing it for so long

00:04:41.690 --> 00:04:44.530
that we've actually seen
kids graduate and they're off

00:04:44.530 --> 00:04:46.790
to college and doing great things.

00:04:46.790 --> 00:04:49.060
So it's, that's a neat experience.

00:04:49.060 --> 00:04:50.360
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Wonderful.

00:04:50.360 --> 00:04:52.950
So in those projects
that you're working on,

00:04:52.950 --> 00:04:56.070
do you see that they're now
different or new opportunities

00:04:56.070 --> 00:04:58.800
for youth to get involved with
classical music as opposed

00:04:58.800 --> 00:05:00.100
to when you were growing up?

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:03.150
Or is it just new packaging for
the same types of engagement?

00:05:03.150 --> 00:05:06.320
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins:
That's a good question.

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:11.680
I, well, the problem with,
the problem I didn't have

00:05:11.680 --> 00:05:15.620
when I was growing up was
I didn't have the challenge

00:05:15.620 --> 00:05:18.330
of their being too
many options for me.

00:05:18.330 --> 00:05:20.300
None of us kids did, you know?

00:05:20.300 --> 00:05:24.380
And nowadays a lot of
things have happened

00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:27.800
that has almost exacerbated the
problem of trying to get kids

00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:32.690
to music, one of which seems to
be preparing them for college.

00:05:32.690 --> 00:05:34.890
You know, there are all of
these other kinds of things.

00:05:34.890 --> 00:05:37.450
I'm really glad that the folks
who came up with the idea

00:05:37.450 --> 00:05:40.520
of stem [assumed], I'm starting
to believe that it really needs

00:05:40.520 --> 00:05:45.130
to be steam, that there needs
to be an arts component.

00:05:45.130 --> 00:05:49.480
But, so I didn't have all of
those obstacles as they were,

00:05:49.480 --> 00:05:53.230
so I had plenty of time for music.

00:05:53.230 --> 00:05:56.530
I think, and it's, beyond obstacles

00:05:56.530 --> 00:06:01.080
in the 21st century
it's just believing

00:06:01.080 --> 00:06:05.360
that this music has some
application to your life.

00:06:05.360 --> 00:06:10.550
And I've always been
about, if a kid comes to one

00:06:10.550 --> 00:06:12.710
of my childrens' concerts
for example,

00:06:12.710 --> 00:06:14.980
there's a couple things
that I want them to see.

00:06:14.980 --> 00:06:18.330
I want them to see that the
orchestra is probably one

00:06:18.330 --> 00:06:22.750
of the best representations
of a community that exists

00:06:22.750 --> 00:06:26.710
in our society, all different
instruments, all different voices,

00:06:26.710 --> 00:06:32.460
all different sizes, all different
levels of power and strength,

00:06:32.460 --> 00:06:36.810
and weakness, and yet they
figure out a way to work together

00:06:36.810 --> 00:06:39.880
so that this incredible, powerful,
beautiful product happens.

00:06:39.880 --> 00:06:41.460
You know that the diverse group

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:43.630
of individuals working
together for a common good.

00:06:43.630 --> 00:06:45.620
So I want them to see that first

00:06:45.620 --> 00:06:49.070 position:56%
and that their families can work the
same way as an orchestra can work

00:06:49.070 --> 00:06:51.260
and their classrooms
can work the same

00:06:51.260 --> 00:06:55.070
or their neighborhoods can work
the same way as an orchestra does.

00:06:55.070 --> 00:06:57.400
The other thing that I
want them to understand is

00:06:57.400 --> 00:07:01.500
that this music has
a direct relationship

00:07:01.500 --> 00:07:02.800
to their everyday lives.

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:06.800
And so if I do a program
that's about Meter

00:07:06.800 --> 00:07:09.200
and Paulson [assumed] music,
it's really about perseverance.

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:12.320
If I do a program that's
built around the idea

00:07:12.320 --> 00:07:14.180
of orchestration, it's
about teamwork.

00:07:14.180 --> 00:07:16.970
So those kinds of things happen.

00:07:16.970 --> 00:07:19.520
And then I want them to
understand that this orchestra

00:07:19.520 --> 00:07:23.020
on stage is theirs, that
this room is theirs.

00:07:23.020 --> 00:07:24.880
They are welcome at any time.

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:29.570
In fact I make a habit
now of even in Omaha

00:07:29.570 --> 00:07:32.090
at subscription concerts I
am seeing young children.

00:07:32.090 --> 00:07:35.580
Right? And if they're
sitting in the first row,

00:07:35.580 --> 00:07:38.280
they get a fist bump
from me on the way out.

00:07:38.280 --> 00:07:41.210
You know, I give them
some wow goofy eye,

00:07:41.210 --> 00:07:44.230 position:56%
because they though they were coming
to one of these [inaudible] and all

00:07:44.230 --> 00:07:48.180
of the sudden the conductor's
fist bumping them at a concert?

00:07:48.180 --> 00:07:49.480
Where's the decorum in that?

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:52.860
Well I don't care where it is,
I want them to feel welcome.

00:07:52.860 --> 00:07:54.810
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Well
it's very refreshing.

00:07:54.810 --> 00:07:58.990 position:56%
I'm appreciative as a concert goer
and musician myself of that attitude

00:07:58.990 --> 00:08:03.890
because I go in to concerts and I
experience people getting chastised

00:08:03.890 --> 00:08:07.110
because they're sharing with their
friend how much they enjoy it.

00:08:07.110 --> 00:08:09.800
And of course there are rules
that should be respected

00:08:09.800 --> 00:08:13.490
like not interrupting your
neighbor and that kind of business

00:08:13.490 --> 00:08:17.530 position:56%
but breaking that wall and making it
a collaborative experience I think

00:08:17.530 --> 00:08:19.040
is such a huge part of it.

00:08:19.040 --> 00:08:20.340
So thank you for that.

00:08:20.340 --> 00:08:23.450
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: I
actually, one time, we did,

00:08:23.450 --> 00:08:29.100
I did a set of it was a long
sweep of like 12 movements.

00:08:29.100 --> 00:08:30.400
It could have been [foreign name]

00:08:30.400 --> 00:08:32.170
but the piece is not
coming to mind just yet.

00:08:32.170 --> 00:08:35.320 position:56%
And I explained to the audience
before that there were 12 movements.

00:08:35.320 --> 00:08:37.950
And the panic on their faces.

00:08:37.950 --> 00:08:41.220
But I said they were short, and in
some instances they were really,

00:08:41.220 --> 00:08:44.540
really short, and so we get to
the end of the first movement

00:08:44.540 --> 00:08:50.340
in the concert and I turn to
the audience and I said, one!

00:08:50.340 --> 00:08:52.000
And then that was all
that was required.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:57.250
It was just break the ice
and now let's have some fun.

00:08:57.250 --> 00:08:58.960
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: So in your
own growing up with music,

00:08:58.960 --> 00:09:00.850
you said when you were
eight years old was

00:09:00.850 --> 00:09:03.270
when you first experienced an
orchestra, was that the moment

00:09:03.270 --> 00:09:04.960
where you said I want to
be a conductor or just

00:09:04.960 --> 00:09:06.260
that I want to be in music?

00:09:06.260 --> 00:09:07.560 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: Isn't that funny?

00:09:07.560 --> 00:09:09.860
That's the moment I said that
I want to be a conductor.

00:09:09.860 --> 00:09:11.350
There was something about this man,

00:09:11.350 --> 00:09:12.650
Russell Stanger [assumed]
was his name,

00:09:12.650 --> 00:09:14.000
this was the Norfolk
Symphony Orchestra,

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:15.850
now it's the Virginia
Symphony, Joanne's [inaudible],

00:09:15.850 --> 00:09:20.690
there was something about
the sound first of all,

00:09:20.690 --> 00:09:23.040
I had never heard an
orchestra before.

00:09:23.040 --> 00:09:30.800
But then maybe it was his movements
or whatever his exuberance,

00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:35.960 position:56%
whatever it was, there was
something about him that said to me,

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:38.440
that's the fun spot down there.

00:09:38.440 --> 00:09:41.490
That's the spot that's
closest to all of that sound.

00:09:41.490 --> 00:09:44.440
It's not the guy with the long
blonde hair playing the snare drum.

00:09:44.440 --> 00:09:46.080
Although that looks pretty cool.

00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:50.850
But this guy was just you know,
all over the place with this music.

00:09:50.850 --> 00:09:55.780
And I like now to in
McDonald's the restaurant a lot

00:09:55.780 --> 00:09:59.230
of McDonald's play lands
they would have those pits

00:09:59.230 --> 00:10:02.680
with all plastic colored
balls and nets around it.

00:10:02.680 --> 00:10:05.680
And my kids would love to go in
there and get under them and dive

00:10:05.680 --> 00:10:08.680
and hide and I said for me
that's what sound is like.

00:10:08.680 --> 00:10:11.220 position:56%
That's what it's like being on the
podium is like being on one of those

00:10:11.220 --> 00:10:13.020
and you're just surrounded
by sound and so

00:10:13.020 --> 00:10:14.320
that was the thing
that got me right away.

00:10:14.320 --> 00:10:17.280
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: So how did you get
from that eight year old person

00:10:17.280 --> 00:10:21.340
with a vision and sort of idea
of the future for themselves

00:10:21.340 --> 00:10:25.360
to being a professional conductor?

00:10:25.360 --> 00:10:28.530
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: At the very
beginning, and when I talk

00:10:28.530 --> 00:10:32.760
to grown ups about how we relate
to children, one of the things

00:10:32.760 --> 00:10:37.750
that I make note of with them is
that when I came home and said

00:10:37.750 --> 00:10:41.880
in my neighborhood, in the hood,
that I wanted to be a conductor,

00:10:41.880 --> 00:10:45.670
no one ever looked at
me and said no dude.

00:10:45.670 --> 00:10:47.560
Young black boys don't
grow up to be conductors.

00:10:47.560 --> 00:10:49.950
Nobody ever said that to me.

00:10:49.950 --> 00:10:52.840
In fact, you know a
lot of times I got oh,

00:10:52.840 --> 00:10:55.040
you're going to be the first
black Leonard Bernstein.

00:10:55.040 --> 00:10:56.340
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Nice.

00:10:56.340 --> 00:10:57.640
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: You
know, I was showed,

00:10:57.640 --> 00:10:59.270
but that tells you
something Bernstein's impact,

00:10:59.270 --> 00:11:02.490
that even in that neighborhood
people knew that name.

00:11:02.490 --> 00:11:06.420
And so we have to be careful
what words we use when we talk

00:11:06.420 --> 00:11:09.330
to children about their dreams and
about their goals in their lives

00:11:09.330 --> 00:11:12.680
and no one clipped
my wings as it were.

00:11:12.680 --> 00:11:15.640
So that was the first
thing that happened.

00:11:15.640 --> 00:11:22.950
But then it, the very next year was
fourth grade and that was the year

00:11:22.950 --> 00:11:25.130
that could start to play
an instrument, and so,

00:11:25.130 --> 00:11:26.690 position:56%
but everyone had to start on violin.

00:11:26.690 --> 00:11:27.990
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Oh, really?

00:11:27.990 --> 00:11:30.180
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: And
this was pre-desegretation.

00:11:30.180 --> 00:11:37.740
And what I learned later as a grown
up, talk about fortuitousness,

00:11:37.740 --> 00:11:43.950 position:56%
I made that word up, but I went back

00:11:43.950 --> 00:11:45.780
to visit my elementary
school principal

00:11:45.780 --> 00:11:47.870
as a grown up, she's
now an old lady.

00:11:47.870 --> 00:11:52.350
And she recounted the story of how
she, and she was a little lady,

00:11:52.350 --> 00:11:54.560
you know like this, Miss Robertson,

00:11:54.560 --> 00:11:57.070
