it must [inaudible] of all my
neighbors probably, you know,

00:13:02.570 --> 00:13:03.870
there I was with my tubas.

00:13:03.870 --> 00:13:06.820
And I played cello in the
orchestra, tuba in the band.

00:13:06.820 --> 00:13:10.080
And also what had happened
in that seventh grade year,

00:13:10.080 --> 00:13:15.680
was my string orchestra teacher
asked who wanted to try to conduct.

00:13:15.680 --> 00:13:18.670
And I raised my hand of course
and I got up and I remember I was

00:13:18.670 --> 00:13:20.650
in three four time and
three four is an art

00:13:20.650 --> 00:13:23.140 position:56%
so there's an extra motion there
that you don't know what to do with.

00:13:23.140 --> 00:13:25.270
So I couldn't get right, and I
said that's alright I don't want

00:13:25.270 --> 00:13:26.570
to do it.

00:13:26.570 --> 00:13:27.870
And he goes no, no, no.

00:13:27.870 --> 00:13:29.170
And he grabbed my hand and he
showed me and then he's like oh.

00:13:29.170 --> 00:13:32.100
So that was my first
conductor experience.

00:13:32.100 --> 00:13:34.700
I mean, outside of
when I was really small

00:13:34.700 --> 00:13:38.230
and I would take my army
soldiers, plastic army soldiers,

00:13:38.230 --> 00:13:40.580
and set them up like an orchestra
and conduct them in my bedroom.

00:13:40.580 --> 00:13:41.880
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Oh really?

00:13:41.880 --> 00:13:43.180
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: I
used to tell people

00:13:43.180 --> 00:13:44.810
that my first conducting job
was as as a military band.

00:13:44.810 --> 00:13:46.110
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Awesome.

00:13:46.110 --> 00:13:47.410
Cool.

00:13:47.410 --> 00:13:48.710
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: But you know,

00:13:48.710 --> 00:13:52.080
then I ultimately chose my
undergraduate school based

00:13:52.080 --> 00:13:54.850
on the ability to have
opportunity to conduct

00:13:54.850 --> 00:13:56.270
that was [inaudible] territory.

00:13:56.270 --> 00:14:03.010
I had gone, I had played every
summer I got to go to band camp

00:14:03.010 --> 00:14:06.250
in Williamsburg playing tuba
and orchestra camp later

00:14:06.250 --> 00:14:07.830
in the summer playing cello.

00:14:07.830 --> 00:14:10.060
Well, I wanted to go to
orchestra camp playing tuba

00:14:10.060 --> 00:14:11.980
so I could be the only person
playing the instrument.

00:14:11.980 --> 00:14:17.540
So sure enough summer of my junior
year I got to go playing tuba.

00:14:17.540 --> 00:14:21.840
And I met the tuba teacher
at Shenandoah Conservatory,

00:14:21.840 --> 00:14:25.340
Fred Marzan [assumed] and he said,
you know if you come to Shenandoah

00:14:25.340 --> 00:14:27.560
as a tuba major instead of cello
I'll let you be the student

00:14:27.560 --> 00:14:29.170
conductor of my brass choir.

00:14:29.170 --> 00:14:34.330
Done! And so it was kind of
a neat little ride there.

00:14:34.330 --> 00:14:37.220
And then it was a school
small enough

00:14:37.220 --> 00:14:39.800
that all the ensembles
had student conductors.

00:14:39.800 --> 00:14:42.970
So every year I was a student
conductor of some ensemeble.

00:14:42.970 --> 00:14:45.540
And actually got to do
a conducting recital

00:14:45.540 --> 00:14:49.210 position:56%
which no one had ever done before
so it was a really neat opportunity.

00:14:49.210 --> 00:14:50.510
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Excellent.

00:14:50.510 --> 00:14:51.810
Growing up and kind of through
your undergraduate period,

00:14:51.810 --> 00:14:55.040
were they any specific pieces
that really clicked for you

00:14:55.040 --> 00:15:01.190 position:56%
or specific composers who made you
realize you were doing what you were

00:15:01.190 --> 00:15:02.490
meant to do?

00:15:02.490 --> 00:15:03.790
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: Yes.

00:15:03.790 --> 00:15:11.350
Oh. One in particular was the hymn
that's in Jupiter, that's embedded

00:15:11.350 --> 00:15:13.820
in Gustav Holst's Jupiter, you know

00:15:13.820 --> 00:15:17.050
that beautiful hymn that's
just sort of stuck there.

00:15:17.050 --> 00:15:20.920
That always transformed me,
transported me to another place.

00:15:20.920 --> 00:15:26.010
The same thing with that same
kind of music in Gershwin Rhapsody

00:15:26.010 --> 00:15:30.780
and blue for example, it always
sent me some place really special.

00:15:30.780 --> 00:15:35.860
And then the slow section
of the last movement

00:15:35.860 --> 00:15:37.210
of Moller's First Symphony.

00:15:37.210 --> 00:15:43.040
You know, Beethoven said that
music is the one incorporeal,

00:15:43.040 --> 00:15:45.870
intangible entrance into the
higher world of knowledge,

00:15:45.870 --> 00:15:49.600
which understands man kind but
which man kind can not understand.

00:15:49.600 --> 00:15:54.940
He's basically saying it knows
us though we know it not.

00:15:54.940 --> 00:15:59.420
To extend that out I always
say that we spend our lives

00:15:59.420 --> 00:16:03.980
as artists working on that
the substance of music

00:16:03.980 --> 00:16:06.760
so that we can try to get
to the essence of music,

00:16:06.760 --> 00:16:10.290 position:56%
but we will never be able to put the
essence of music really into words.

00:16:10.290 --> 00:16:11.590
You know? It's not enough

00:16:11.590 --> 00:16:14.220
to say forte means strong,
forte means confident.

00:16:14.220 --> 00:16:17.080
It still won't get you to
what, to one of those moments.

00:16:17.080 --> 00:16:21.960
And so those were moments and
then they remain moments for me.

00:16:21.960 --> 00:16:26.860
And in many instances they're
worshipful moments for me.

00:16:26.860 --> 00:16:31.510
It is my favorite time to
worship is when I'm conducting.

00:16:31.510 --> 00:16:34.760
So it's, yes, there have
always been places like that.

00:16:34.760 --> 00:16:39.580
And when I come back to
them now as a grown up,

00:16:39.580 --> 00:16:42.710
they have an extra meaning
because they are a part

00:16:42.710 --> 00:16:47.150
of my aesthetic history as
much as they are just you know,

00:16:47.150 --> 00:16:48.550
a piece that I'm working on.

00:16:48.550 --> 00:16:51.190 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Do you ever associate
those or other pieces with sort

00:16:51.190 --> 00:16:56.830
of milestone life events?

00:16:56.830 --> 00:16:58.130
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: There
are moments like that,

00:16:58.130 --> 00:17:02.770
I think for example the first time
I heard the opera Dido Aeneas.

00:17:02.770 --> 00:17:06.670
I sat in the library and
New England Conservatory,

00:17:06.670 --> 00:17:08.370
you know what library
I'm talking about.

00:17:08.370 --> 00:17:09.830
And I wept like a baby.

00:17:09.830 --> 00:17:11.130
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Oh wow!

00:17:11.130 --> 00:17:16.100
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: I had the
head phones on and I'm just.

00:17:16.100 --> 00:17:20.320
So I know exactly where I
was at that moment you know

00:17:20.320 --> 00:17:24.200
and there are other
places like that.

00:17:24.200 --> 00:17:31.380
In fact there was a moment
during the, doing the planets,

00:17:31.380 --> 00:17:33.590
the Venus Movement by
the way is another one

00:17:33.590 --> 00:17:36.900
of those exquisite moments for me.

00:17:36.900 --> 00:17:41.080
But during that Jupiter, during
that hymn in that Jupiter, I was,

00:17:41.080 --> 00:17:45.460
I didn't do it on purpose but, and
I was guest conducting somewhere

00:17:45.460 --> 00:17:46.760
and my wife and my father

00:17:46.760 --> 00:17:49.990
in law were sitting
together in the audience.

00:17:49.990 --> 00:17:52.480
And during that moment when it got

00:17:52.480 --> 00:17:55.890
to its grandest place I just
let go of the orchestra.

00:17:55.890 --> 00:17:57.190
I didn't wave my arms.

00:17:57.190 --> 00:17:59.820
I just stayed in that
position and I think I was,

00:17:59.820 --> 00:18:03.940
what I was saying is look at how
much bigger than we are this is.

00:18:03.940 --> 00:18:07.640
And there was no movement that
was, that seemed to be necessary.

00:18:07.640 --> 00:18:08.940
And they got it!

00:18:08.940 --> 00:18:10.240
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Wow!

00:18:10.240 --> 00:18:13.870
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: And my father in
law said look at what he's doing.

00:18:13.870 --> 00:18:15.260
And my wife said oh he's gone.

00:18:15.260 --> 00:18:18.180
She told me that later.

00:18:18.180 --> 00:18:21.830
She's like he's gone.

00:18:21.830 --> 00:18:23.130
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Very cool.

00:18:23.130 --> 00:18:27.100
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: And there,
engima, the nimrod variations,

00:18:27.100 --> 00:18:31.010
I remember being at a
conducting camp which sounds

00:18:31.010 --> 00:18:34.090
like the biggest nerd
festival you can ever imagine.

00:18:34.090 --> 00:18:38.300
And it was, I wasn't conducting at
the time, but it was being played

00:18:38.300 --> 00:18:41.330 position:56%
in the room and I thought to myself,
I was already married by then,

00:18:41.330 --> 00:18:42.980
and I thought to myself,

00:18:42.980 --> 00:18:46.220
that describes how much I
love my wife right there.

00:18:46.220 --> 00:18:48.650
And I told her that later.

00:18:48.650 --> 00:18:53.020
So whenever I'm in that music
I think about that moment

00:18:53.020 --> 00:18:55.730
that I just made that
sort of discovery.

00:18:55.730 --> 00:18:59.250
You know, at summer
music camp for grown ups.

00:18:59.250 --> 00:19:01.120
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: What was
her response to that?

00:19:01.120 --> 00:19:02.420
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: Oh it
got me some major points.

00:19:02.420 --> 00:19:03.720
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Oh great.

00:19:03.720 --> 00:19:07.370
Did she ever request it on the
CD player or something like that?

00:19:07.370 --> 00:19:09.280
No? Or did you surprise it?

00:19:09.280 --> 00:19:12.940
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: No, she doesn't
but often I will share music

00:19:12.940 --> 00:19:19.560
with her if I'm some place else
that speaks of our relationship.

00:19:19.560 --> 00:19:23.140
If it touches me in a certain
way I will send her a link

00:19:23.140 --> 00:19:26.080
to it and you know.

00:19:26.080 --> 00:19:27.580
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Neat.

00:19:27.580 --> 00:19:28.880
Yes.

00:19:28.880 --> 00:19:30.180
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: Romantic.

00:19:30.180 --> 00:19:31.480
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Wonderful.

00:19:31.480 --> 00:19:33.990
So after you did grad school,
what was the path from there?

00:19:33.990 --> 00:19:35.290
Were you an assistant?

00:19:35.290 --> 00:19:36.590
Did you do festivals?

00:19:36.590 --> 00:19:37.890 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: It's interesting.

00:19:37.890 --> 00:19:40.190
I didn't have, you know
there is no rhyme or reason,

00:19:40.190 --> 00:19:44.450
there's no prescribed
route in this country.

00:19:44.450 --> 00:19:47.570
You know, you don't, your not a
repetiteur one point and then all

00:19:47.570 --> 00:19:51.870
of the sudden you're,
you get your chance.

00:19:51.870 --> 00:19:56.100
My first job out of graduate school
was at a small college in Chicago,

00:19:56.100 --> 00:20:00.250 position:56%
North Park College is now North Park
University, small Christian college.

00:20:00.250 --> 00:20:03.580
Which is, believe it or
not where I met my wife.

00:20:03.580 --> 00:20:09.030
And it was, it was a
liberal arts college.

00:20:09.030 --> 00:20:10.840
You know? I think, first

00:20:10.840 --> 00:20:13.970
of all there was only eight
people on the music faculty.

00:20:13.970 --> 00:20:18.240
So it meant that I did a
lot of stuff, you know,

00:20:18.240 --> 00:20:20.770
taught orchestration, I taught
sophomore theory one year,

00:20:20.770 --> 00:20:23.870
I taught conduct, all three levels
of conducting, brass methods,

00:20:23.870 --> 00:20:25.780
string methods because
I played both.

00:20:25.780 --> 00:20:29.300 position:56%
One year I taught percussion methods
because I was the youngest person

00:20:29.300 --> 00:20:32.130
on the faculty and therefore
the person most likely

00:20:32.130 --> 00:20:33.560
to have remembered it from college.

00:20:33.560 --> 00:20:36.540
It was pretty funny.

00:20:36.540 --> 00:20:38.040
But when I called my teacher back

00:20:38.040 --> 00:20:39.590
in New England said oh
my gosh you're not going

00:20:39.590 --> 00:20:41.810
to believe what they have
me doing for $15,000 a year.

00:20:41.810 --> 00:20:43.220
He said what are you talking about?

00:20:43.220 --> 00:20:44.520
That's a great job for you!

00:20:44.520 --> 00:20:46.570
You're not going to always
be a friend or your fellow,

00:20:46.570 --> 00:20:48.660
you need to learn how to
teach people to play better.

00:20:48.660 --> 00:20:50.170
You know, and he was right.

00:20:50.170 --> 00:20:54.290
So it was, it wasn't a
crummy job, it was just not,

00:20:54.290 --> 00:20:56.290
it wasn't the New England
Conservatory,

00:20:56.290 --> 00:20:57.710
where I had just graduated from.

00:20:57.710 --> 00:21:01.510
And that was a whole different
level of student musicians.

00:21:01.510 --> 00:21:04.360
But it was good for me to be there.

00:21:04.360 --> 00:21:08.610
And I've always, not always
believed but certainly much

00:21:08.610 --> 00:21:11.160
of my life I believe that you
bloom where you're planted.

00:21:11.160 --> 00:21:14.070
And you try to grow
wherever you are,

00:21:14.070 --> 00:21:16.620
contribute whatever you
can while you're there.

00:21:16.620 --> 00:21:20.370
But to not let a day go by
where you don't learn something.

00:21:20.370 --> 00:21:25.570 position:56%
And I had always said that, excuse
me, that more than anything I wanted

00:21:25.570 --> 00:21:27.150
to be prepared for the next thing.

00:21:27.150 --> 00:21:30.890
So, you know, that job led
to another university job

00:21:30.890 --> 00:21:32.970
at the University of Tennessee in
Chattanooga and I was only there

00:21:32.970 --> 00:21:36.110
for two years because I taken
a Richmond Symphony audition.

00:21:36.110 --> 00:21:40.690
The assistant conductor audition.

00:21:40.690 --> 00:21:45.680
And I made finals and
then didn't hear anything.

00:21:45.680 --> 00:21:48.710
And it just so happened that Marian
Alsip is a very good friend of mine

00:21:48.710 --> 00:21:50.380 position:56%
and she had also taken the audition.

00:21:50.380 --> 00:21:52.600
And so after a while I called
Marian and I said Marian,

00:21:52.600 --> 00:21:55.370
I haven't heard a thing
from Richmond, have you?

00:21:55.370 --> 00:21:57.610
She goes, yes, they hired me.

00:21:57.610 --> 00:21:58.910
I went oh!

00:21:58.910 --> 00:22:00.210
Congratulations!

00:22:00.210 --> 00:22:04.130
We still crack up about that.

00:22:04.130 --> 00:22:09.120
And then her career
took off and she left.

00:22:09.120 --> 00:22:12.190
She was leaving, preparing to
leave, and so they called me

00:22:12.190 --> 00:22:14.980
and said you know, we don't
want to do another audition,

00:22:14.980 --> 00:22:16.830
quite frankly you were
our second choice anyway,

00:22:16.830 --> 00:22:18.230
if you want the job,
the job is yours.

00:22:18.230 --> 00:22:19.530
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Wow.

00:22:19.530 --> 00:22:21.060
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: So sure enough
I got that job and I was there

00:22:21.060 --> 00:22:25.240
for I don't know how long,
five, six, seven years maybe.

00:22:25.240 --> 00:22:28.130
And then I got a job with
the Florida Orchestra

00:22:28.130 --> 00:22:31.000
as the resident conductor there.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:33.050
And that was great.

00:22:33.050 --> 00:22:36.590
And the best thing about that
job was that believe it or not,

00:22:36.590 --> 00:22:39.740
was that the music director
was hardly ever there.

00:22:39.740 --> 00:22:44.880 position:56%
So I got to learn how to do a lot of
music director stuff, meet people,

00:22:44.880 --> 00:22:51.120
engage people, go on, ask
for you know for funding.

00:22:51.120 --> 00:22:55.940
I became really an integral part
of the community getting on boards

00:22:55.940 --> 00:22:57.540
and involved in the life

00:22:57.540 --> 00:23:00.360
of the community outside
of the concert hall.

00:23:00.360 --> 00:23:03.250
And that was really the formative
years for me of learning how

00:23:03.250 --> 00:23:06.070
to be a conductor was really
learning how to be an artist

00:23:06.070 --> 00:23:08.670
in a community and
how important it was.

00:23:08.670 --> 00:23:13.550
You know, when I left Florida
to go to Detroit, I guess that's

00:23:13.550 --> 00:23:17.960
where we went next, I was
just walking down the street

00:23:17.960 --> 00:23:19.840
and a lady stops at a red light.

00:23:19.840 --> 00:23:21.140
Gets out of her car.

00:23:21.140 --> 00:23:23.090
And comes and hugs me and goes
oh I'm going to miss you so much.

00:23:23.090 --> 00:23:24.390
I don't know who that lady was.

00:23:24.390 --> 00:23:25.690
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Wow.

00:23:25.690 --> 00:23:27.340
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: Yes, it
was a really neat thing.

00:23:27.340 --> 00:23:30.580
And it wasn't because I'm the
greatest conductor they have ever

00:23:30.580 --> 00:23:32.650
seen but it was because they
had someone who really cared

00:23:32.650 --> 00:23:35.650
about their lives and their
childrens' lives and wanted

00:23:35.650 --> 00:23:42.440 position:56%
to be partners with them in the
raising of their children and wanted

00:23:42.440 --> 00:23:45.740
to be partners with them
in enhancing the quality

00:23:45.740 --> 00:23:47.040
of life in their community.

00:23:47.040 --> 00:23:49.030
That's what they saw,
that's what they loved more

00:23:49.030 --> 00:23:50.750
than anything else I think.

00:23:50.750 --> 00:23:55.550
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: So how do you try
to teach that kind of set of values

00:23:55.550 --> 00:23:59.620
to younger conducting colleagues
or students or even you know,

00:23:59.620 --> 00:24:02.820
relatives who are young
growing up or your kids as well?

00:24:02.820 --> 00:24:06.700
Because I think a lot of those
things that conductors deal

00:24:06.700 --> 00:24:10.090
with are life skills that
maybe not everyone realizes.

00:24:10.090 --> 00:24:12.200 position:56%
So you can go be a leader in your
community whether you're a conductor

00:24:12.200 --> 00:24:14.270
or you're a business
person or whatever else.

00:24:14.270 --> 00:24:17.720
But yes, I'd love to
just hear your thoughts.

00:24:17.720 --> 00:24:21.880
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: Well you know
people don't follow great leaders

00:24:21.880 --> 00:24:24.340
because they're necessarily
great people.

00:24:24.340 --> 00:24:29.520
Great leaders present visions of
things that are larger than us

00:24:29.520 --> 00:24:32.160
that we want to be a part of.

00:24:32.160 --> 00:24:36.860
And I think first and foremost
you have to live your life

00:24:36.860 --> 00:24:38.760
in a way that's reverent.

00:24:38.760 --> 00:24:43.420
So that no one ever
gets, no one ever thinks

00:24:43.420 --> 00:24:45.610
that you think you are more
important than the music.

00:24:45.610 --> 00:24:50.320
And I think part of the success
that I've had as a conductor is

00:24:50.320 --> 00:24:53.310
that when I'm in front of an
orchestra they all understand

00:24:53.310 --> 00:24:57.810
that together we are fortunate
first of all to be in this room,

00:24:57.810 --> 00:25:00.950
and that we could be flipping
hamburgers but we're not.

00:25:00.950 --> 00:25:04.740 position:56%
We are doing something that's really
beyond all of us and I say to them,

00:25:04.740 --> 00:25:10.810
you know you have to realize that
this music was here long before us

00:25:10.810 --> 00:25:13.700
and it'll be here long
after we're gone.

00:25:13.700 --> 00:25:16.380
We will never measure
up to this music.

00:25:16.380 --> 00:25:21.440
But it's in the trying to
measure up that we become artists.

00:25:21.440 --> 00:25:24.750
And the moment that we understand
those parameters and we try

00:25:24.750 --> 00:25:27.780
to measure up not only
do we become artists

00:25:27.780 --> 00:25:29.910
but hopefully we will
become servants.

00:25:29.910 --> 00:25:32.240
So that we are really the conduits.

00:25:32.240 --> 00:25:34.760
So that this music
can get communicated

00:25:34.760 --> 00:25:37.120
because these composers
don't write music

00:25:37.120 --> 00:25:40.800
to demonstrate their
skill at music theory.

00:25:40.800 --> 00:25:44.630
They write for, to help us
understand that we were made

00:25:44.630 --> 00:25:48.900
to be better than what we
may have thought we were.

